The Certificate II in Electrotechnology is ideal for Year 11 and 12 students wanting to gain an insight into the electrical industry. This course will suit students who enjoy problem-solving, working with technology and who want a career in the Electrotechnology industry.
All Trade College students undertake a minimum of 75 days of workplace learning as part of our flagship Industry Work Experience Program.

userdata.description: Plumbing is one of the top three occupations in the construction industry with both general and specialised plumbers in demand. Plumbers with different specialisations are areas of particularly high demand. Year 11 and Year 12 students will develop the practical skills and knowledge to use hand and power tools, carry out welding, read and interpret plans, and calculate quantities and other measurements. Students will learn about working safely and effectively in the workplace and how to adhere to the industryâ€™s regulations and standards. Certificate I in Construction provides students with an introduction to the construction industry. This course is perfect for students to learn how to use basic construction tools and materials, all the essential Work Health and Safety (WHS) requirements and how to apply them to your job on a day-to-day basis, how to effectively communicate and understand the culture, occupations, job roles and employer expectations in the construction world.
All Trade College students undertake a minimum of 75 days of workplace learning as part of our flagship Industry Work Experience Program.

userdata.description:
The automotive industry offers the opportunity to get involved in a broad-based skills area driven by new technologies. Automotive employment opportunities are emerging in diagnostic, servicing, repair and maintenance roles across Australia.
The Certificate II Automotive will set a Year 11 and Year 12 student on the path to finding a school-based apprenticeship in a wide range of automotive occupations including as a light or heavy vehicle mechanic, an automotive electrician, a diesel fitter or an outdoor power equipment technician. You may also like to seek employment as a vehicle service assistant or as an automotive parts interpreter.
All Trade College students undertake a minimum of 75 days of workplace learning as part of our flagship Industry Work Experience Program.

userdata.description:
The certificate II Engineering is ideal for Year 11 and 12 students interested in exposure to an engineering or related working environment with a view to entering into employment in that area. This course will set you on the path to pursue an apprenticeship in a wide range of engineering jobs including fitting and turning, sheet metal fabrication, boiler making, welding, casting and moulding, and diesel, mechanical or electrical fitting.
All Trade College students undertake a minimum of 75 days of workplace learning as part of our flagship Industry Work Experience Program.

userdata.description: At the Trade College, our essential learning program allows you to earn a Queensland Certificate of Education (QCE) outcome at the end of Year 12 by studying Queensland Curriculum and Assessment Authority (QCAA) registered subjects. The College curriculum is centred on the components of the Queensland senior curriculum that are most relevant to young apprentices and trainees such as Essential English, Essential Mathematics, Business Studies and Industry Preparation.

Nail the Connection as a hairdressing assistant with this pre-apprenticeship qualification. This course is designed to teach students routine tasks and procedures as well as team and group work that shows employers you are dedicated to building a career in hairdressing. All Trade College students undertake a minimum of 75 days of workplace learning as part of our flagship Industry Work Experience Program.

userdata.description:
Students gather in the College Hall every Wednesday to celebrate their achievements and recognise students who recently secured school-based apprenticeships.
The College Hall also doubles as an indoor sports centre where students engage in a variety of recreational activities.
The College Hall is then transformed in November each year for the annual Awards and Year 12 Graduation Ceremony where a number of academic and industry Special Awards are presented.
